children.name: description
children.characters: This is the kit for creating simple Mixed Reality UI layouts. It includes 2D versions of the UI controls in the Mixed Reality Toolkit (MRTK) for Unity. Once you make a flat layout here, it is easy to recreate with Mixed Reality Toolbox components, then you can play with z-position, rotation, etc within Unity.

children.name: description
children.characters: New to Mixed Reality? Visit aka.ms/mixedrealitydocs for all the info you’ll need to make a Mixed Reality Experience.

children.name: description
children.characters: Visit here for info specifically about designing and prototyping for Mixed Reality.

children.name: title
children.characters: What’s included? (Pages from the left menu)

children.name: description
children.characters:
Change Log Version and updates to this file documented 
UI Gallery Good place to view available UI controls.

Viewports Make your layouts here.

children.name: questions
children.characters:
Components The master collection of the UI controls, plus states. You can also swap or add button icons here.

Examples This page demonstrates what you can build using MRTK Figma Toolkit. It has examples of UI layout and storyboarding.

children.name: description
children.characters:
Segoe UI fonts are provided as system fonts in Windows. For Mac users, please visit this page to download Segoe UI fonts.
https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/uwp/design/downloads/#fonts

children.name: title
children.characters: Building your UI layout or storyboard

children.name: description
children.characters: The best place to build your layouts is on the Viewports page. The frames are the proper pixel size for HoloLens 2 and the original HoloLens. You can also copy the viewport to a new page.

children.name: description
children.characters: Drag the UI you need from the Assets panel, or copy/paste from the UI Gallery page.

children.name: description
children.characters: Most UI controls in this toolkit have states. To switch between them, use the dropdown menu in the Design panel on the right.

children.name: description
children.characters:
You can choose from a variety of button icons using the dropdown menu in the Design panel on the right,. It’s just like switching between states. 

You can swap in your own icons or add to the list using the Icon component on the Components page.

children.name: description
children.characters:
Figma measures things in pixels, but Mixed Reality is in the real world, and measured in millimeters. 

To make the controls here reasonable to work with, here are the scales we used.

HoloLens 2 UI
3px=1mm scale
Near interaction - user can touch the UI (about 45 cm away)

HoloLens 1 UI
1px=1mm scale
Far interaction - user the user can’t touch this UI directly, but uses hand rays, controller rays or gaze to aim and interact (about 2 m away)

children.name: description
children.characters:
Most of the controls available in the UI Gallery in this Figma file are a 2D recreation of a control available in the MRTK for Unity as prefabs. These prefabs can be found in MRTK Toolbox.

The ideas is, you or your Unity expert can easily recreate any layouts you make here in Unity, because the building blocks are visually the same.

You can learn about MRTK for Unity on this page:
https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/mixed-reality/mrtk-unity/

children.name: description
children.characters:
Once you have imported MRTK’s Foundation and Tools packages into Unity, the Toolbox can be found under the Mixed Reality Toolkit menu item at the top.

Double click any control to drop it into your Unity scene. You can also find corresponding prefabs by searching in the Project panel.

To learn more about how to install Unity and configure MRTK, check out MRTK-Unity Beginner Tutorial:
https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/mixed-reality/develop/unity/tutorials/mr-learning-base-01
